 '''Kiev Pechersk Lavra''' or '''Kyiv Pechersk Lavra'''<ref>[http://www.rada.gov.ua/ukraine.htm Verkhovna Rada Portal] This is the official English spelling used by the Ukrainian government</ref><ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/city/detail/69789/  Parliament votes down law on preservation of Kyiv Pechersk Lavra complex] Interfax-Ukraine, 16 June 2010 at 10:42</ref>({{lang-uk|Києво-Печерська лавра, ''Kyievo-Pechers'ka lavra''}}, {{lang-ru|link=no|Киeво-Печерская лавра, ''Kievo-Pecherskaya lavra''}}), also known as the '''Kiev Monastery of the Caves''', is a historic [[Monastery#Orthodox Christian monasteries|Orthodox Christian monastery]] which gave its name to [[Pechersk Raion|one of the city districts]] where it is located in [[Kiev]].

-Since its foundation as the [[cave monastery]] in 1051<ref>[Magocsi P.R. A History of Ukraine. University of Toronto Press: Toronto, 1996. p 98.]</ref> the Lavra has been a preeminent center of [[Eastern Orthodox Christianity]] in Eastern Europe. Together with the [[Saint Sophia Cathedral in Kiev|Saint Sophia Cathedral]], it is inscribed as a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]].<ref name="Kyiv Pechersk Lavra, St. Sophia Cathedral remain on UNESCO’s World Heritage List">[http://www.interfax.co.uk/ukraine-news/kyiv-pechersk-lavra-st-sophia-cathedral-remain-on-unescos-world-heritage-list/ Kyiv Pechersk Lavra, St. Sophia Cathedral remain on UNESCO’s World Heritage List], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (20 June 2013)</ref>{{#tag:ref|Late 2010 a monitoring mission of [[UNESCO]] was visiting the Kiev Pechersk Lavra to check on situation of the site. At the time the [[Ministry of Culture (Ukraine)|Minister of Culture]] [[Mykhailo Kulynyak]] stated the historic site along with the [[Saint Sophia's Cathedral, Kiev|Saint Sophia Cathedral]] was not threatened by the "black list" of the organization.<ref>[http://mincult.kmu.gov.ua/mincult/uk/publish/article/238820 «Софії Київській та Києво-Печерській лаврі «чорний список» ЮНЕСКО не загрожує» – Міністр культури Михайло Кулиняк]</ref> The [[World Heritage Committee]] of UNESCO decided in June 2013 that Kiev Pechersk Lavra, and St. Sofia Cathedral and related monastery buildings would remain on the [[World Heritage List]].<ref name="Kyiv Pechersk Lavra, St. Sophia Cathedral remain on UNESCO’s World Heritage List"/>|group=nb}} The monastery complex is considered a separate national historic-cultural preserve (sanctuary), the national status to which was granted on 13 March 1996.<ref>[http://zakon1.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/main.cgi?nreg=181%2F96&p=1260343170231885 Про надання статусу національного Києво-Печерському державному історико-культурному заповіднику]</ref> The Lavra is not only located in another part of the city, but is part of a different national sanctuary than Saint Sophia Cathedral. While being a cultural attraction, the monastery is once again active, with over 100 monks in residence. It was named one of the [[Seven Wonders of Ukraine]] on 21 August 2007, based on voting by experts and the internet community.
+Since its foundation as the [[cave monastery]] in 1051<ref>[Magocsi P.R. A History of Ukraine. University of Toronto Press: Toronto, 1996. p 98.]</ref> the Lavra has been a preeminent center of [[Eastern Orthodox Christianity]] in Eastern Europe. Together with the [[Saint Sophia Cathedral in Kiev|Saint Sophia Cathedral]], it is inscribed as a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]].<ref name="Kyiv Pechersk Lavra, St. Sophia Cathedral remain on UNESCO’s World Heritage List">[http://www.interfax.co.uk/ukraine-news/kyiv-pechersk-lavra-st-sophia-cathedral-remain-on-unescos-world-heritage-list/ Kyiv Pechersk Lavra, St. Sophia Cathedral remain on UNESCO’s World Heritage List], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (20 June 2013)</ref>{{#tag:ref|Late 2010 a monitoring mission of [[UNESCO]] was visiting the Kiev Pechersk Lavra to check on situation of the site. At the time the [[Ministry of Culture (Ukraine)|Minister of Culture]] [[Mykhailo Kulynyak]] stated the historic site along with the [[Saint Sophia's Cathedral, Kiev|Saint Sophia Cathedral]] was not threatened by the "black list" of the organization.<ref>[http://mincult.kmu.gov.ua/mincult/uk/publish/article/238820 «Софії Київській та Києво-Печерській лаврі «чорний список» ЮНЕСКО не загрожує» – Міністр культури Михайло Кулиняк]</ref> The [[World Heritage Committee]] of UNESCO decided in June 2013 that Kiev Pechersk Lavra, and St. Sofia Cathedral and related monastery buildings would remain on the [[World Heritage List]].<ref name="Kyiv Pechersk Lavra, St. Sophia Cathedral remain on UNESCO’s World Heritage List"/>|group=nb}} The monastery complex is considered a separate national historic-cultural preserve (sanctuary), the national status to which was granted on 13 March 1996.<ref>[http://zakon1.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/main.cgi?nreg=181%2F96&p=1260343170231885 Про надання статусу національного Києво-Печерському державному історико-культурному заповіднику]</ref> The Lavra is not only located in another part of the city, but is part of a different national sanctuary than Saint Sophia Cathedral. While being a cultural attraction, the monastery is once again active, with over 100 monks in residence.{{fact}} It was named one of the [[Seven Wonders of Ukraine]] on 21 August 2007, based on voting by experts and the internet community.{{fact}}

 Currently, the jurisdiction over the site is divided between the state museum, National Kiev-Pechersk Historic-Cultural Preserve,<ref>[http://www.kplavra.kiev.ua/#]</ref> and the [[Ukrainian Orthodox Church (Moscow Patriarchate)]] as the site of the chief monastery of that Church and the residence of its leader, [[Onuphrius (Berezovsky)|Metropolitan Onuphrius]].

